subject: ENGLISH
text: What sort of person did Shakespeare mean any one of the following to be: Falstaff, Richard II, Bassanio, Polonius, Banquo, Edmund, Coriolanus? Is the man you choose good or bad, wise or foolish, likable or unlikable?

subject: ENGLISH
text: If in an amateur performance of one of the following plays—Julius Caesar, As You Like It, Twelfth Night, The Tempest—you were given your choice of a character, whom would you choose and why?

subject: ENGLISH
text: What supernatural elements does Shakespeare introduce into any one of the following plays: A Midsummer Night’s Dream, Julius Caesar, Hamlet, Macbeth, The Tempest? Show to what extent the supernatural is apparent to the human persons in the play.

subject: ENGLISH
text: Choose two of the Canterbury Pilgrims and write in prose an account of them based on Chaucer's portraits.

subject: ENGLISH
text: Illustrate from any one of The Canterbury Tales or from The Prologue Chaucer's sly humour.

subject: ENGLISH
text: What was the occasion of the writing of Lycidas by Milton? Show how the poet clothes the real incident in pastoral imagery.

subject: ENGLISH
text: Write a character-sketch and history of Bridget Elia as you have come to know her in The Essays of Elia.

subject: ENGLISH
text: Give an account of the oddities of behaviour and opinion of Sir Roger de Coverley.

subject: ENGLISH
text: Choose any one of Sir Walter Scott’s novels and describe any scene or incident in it that has particularly appealed to you.

subject: ENGLISH
text: Explain as intelligibly as possible the story or the situation in any one of the following poems: Alexander’s Feast, The Rape of the Lock, The Bard, The Cotter’s Saturday Night, Resolution and Independence, An Ode to the West Wind, The Eve of St. Agnes, Horatius, The Forsaken Merman, The Revenge.
